ces the expansion of this remarkable transnational market from its earliest days to the mid-nineteenth century during a period of intense religious struggle in Upper Canada marked by fiery revivals, political betrayals, and bitter church schisms. The Methodist Book Concern occupied a central place in all this conflict as it powerfully shaped and subverted the religious and political identities of Canadian Methodists, bankrolled the bulk of Methodist preaching and missionary activities, enabled and constrained evangelistic efforts among the colony’s Native groups, and clouded Methodist dealings with the British Wesleyans and other religious competitors north of the border. Even more importantly, as Methodists went on to assume a preeminent place in the province’s religious, cultural, and educational life, their ongoing reliance on the Methodist Book Concern played a crucial part in opening the way for what would later become the lasting acceptance and widespread use of American books and periodicals across the province as a whole.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBooks and readingxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aBooks and readingzCanadaxHistory. 0aBooks and readingzCanadaxSociological aspects. 0aMethodist ChurchxPublishing. 0aMethodist ChurchzCanada. 0aPublishers and publishingzCanadaxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Books & Reading.2bisacsh  aAnglicans.  aEgerton Ryerson.  aMethodists.  aNew York Methodist Book Concern.  aPre-Confederation Canada.  aUpper Canada.  abooks.  achurch history.  ahistory of publishing.  aprinting press.  areading.  areligion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org